IF CONDITION:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CASE1:  Github repo {https://github.com/manojpodugu/temp.git} already have pre-existing files.
========
#A) Use "git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories" --> Fetch and merge the existing GitHub repository. 

# EXPLANATION:
#i) Normally, Git expects both repositories/branches to share a common commit history (a common ancestor). If they don't, Git throws an error like "fatal: refusing to merge unrelated histories".
#ii) Use of "--allow-unrelated-histories" in the above command tells git --> "I know these histories are completely separate. Merge them anyway."
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#CASE2: what if, the github repo {https://github.com/manojpodugu/temp.git} is a newly created one.
=======
#i) then, just follow the given steps from 1 to 9. {vomit #A}.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

#7) "git add ." --> Add the files and folders to staging area. {"git status" --> to see staged changes that are ready for the commit}.
#8) "git commit -m "Added local project" --> to commit the staged changes to local ".git/" folder. {"git log" --> to see commit history}.
#9) "git push -u origin main" --> to push all this changes to remote github repo. In this case {https://github.com/manojpodugu/temp.git}.



# NOTE: IMP Commands
#1) "git rm --cached -r ."   --> to remove all the staged changes.
#2) "git status"             --> to see staged changes that are ready for the commit.
#3) "git update-ref -d HEAD" --> To uncommit all the commited changes and send these changes back to "staging area".
#4) "git log"                --> to see commit history.
#5) "git remote -v"          --> to check whether remote repository connected to local or not.



